class Solution:
    def search(self, nums: List[int], target: int) -> int:
        low, high = 0, len(nums) - 1
        while low <= high:
            mid = (low + high) // 2
            if nums[mid] == target:
                return mid
            # left half is sorted
            if nums[low] <= nums[mid]:
                if nums[low] <= target < nums[mid]:
                    high = mid - 1
                else:
                    low = mid + 1
            # right half is sorted
            else:
                if nums[mid] < target <= nums[high]:
                    low = mid + 1
                else:
                    high = mid - 1
        return -1

"""
Approach & Reasoning:
The array is sorted in ascending order but rotated at an unknown pivot. Because all elements are unique, we can use a modified binary search to locate the target in O(log n) time.

Maintain two pointers `low` and `high`. At each step:
- Compute `mid`.
- If `nums[mid] == target`, return `mid`.
- Check if the left half (`low` to `mid`) is sorted (`nums[low] <= nums[mid]`):
  - If yes and `target` lies in this range (`nums[low] <= target < nums[mid]`), search the left half.
  - Otherwise, search the right half.
- Otherwise the right half (`mid` to `high`) must be sorted:
  - If `target` lies in this range (`nums[mid] < target <= nums[high]`), search the right half.
  - Otherwise, search the left half.

Each iteration discards half of the remaining search space because at least one subarray is always monotonically increasing. When the loop ends without finding the target, return -1.

Time Complexity: O(log n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
"""
